ref: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.151, p.656 (1970)
title: Spontaneously fissioning isomers in U, Pu, Am and Cm isotopes

x4freetext: Spontaneously fissioning isomers in U, Pu, Am
and Cm isotopes

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.151, p.656 (1970)

x4freetext: Tandem Van de Graaff accelerator
The targets were produced by vacuum evaporation of
oxides onto 1 mg/cm2 nickel foil. The target material
was distributed over a spot 6-7 cm in diam., and
targets were cut from this foil with a surgical knife
or with a punch. The target thickness varied from 10
to about 30mu-g/cm2. This gives recoil yields higher
than 70% at the beam energies used.
The detectors are polycarbonate
foils (Makrofol)
The cross sections are calculated comparing the isomer
yields with the yield of the 1 ms 244mAm under
identical conditions

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Soviet Journal of Nuclear Physics, Vol.8, p.267 (1969)

x4freetext: Two methods used. The first method is based on the
detection of fission-in-flight of nuclei recoiling out
of a thin target by means of polycarbonate, fission
track detectors.
In the second method, the delayed fissions are
detected by a surface barrier semiconductor counter.
Half-lives shorter than 900 ns are measured by the
fission-in-flight method. The 900 ns 237Np and the
longer lived ones are measured by the ring counter
method and pulsed beam.

x4freetext: - method
Unpublished results by Gangrsky and Sletten indicate
even lower limits for fission decays with T/2  longer
than 1 ms are given in Tbl.3.
Total uncertainty
The largest variation in target thickness
was about 20%. This means that the maximum variation
in recoil yield was kept within +-10%.
